<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="36" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[840,1482,1005,1241]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis box="[840,924,1005,1026]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Etymology</emphasis>
: The name was chosen at a naming and voting session during the taxon expedition and refers to the ‘squad’ of participants that jointly sampled this species during night-time walks in the forest. The taxonomic authority for this species is attributed to all authors of this paper. Following Article 51 C of the Code (
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN" box="[846,971,1139,1161]" journalOrPublisher="International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" refId="ref3780" refString="ICZN. 1999. International code of zoological nomenclature. Edn 4. International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London." title="International code of zoological nomenclature. Edn 4" type="book" year="1999">ICZN, 1999</bibRefCitation>
), the species can be referred to as 
<taxonomicName authority="Schilthuizen et al., 2018" authorityName="Schilthuizen" authorityYear="2018" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="exquadratus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Microparmarion exquadratus</emphasis>
Schilthuizen 
<emphasis box="[1077,1123,1165,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">et al.</emphasis>
, 2018
</taxonomicName>
, provided the full citation of this publication appears in the bibliography or elsewhere in the referring work.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="36" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[840,1482,1272,1428]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis box="[840,919,1272,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simroth" authorityYear="1893" box="[1014,1147,1272,1293]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1014,1147,1272,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Microparmarion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species of Borneo, 
<emphasis box="[1344,1365,1272,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M</emphasis>
. ex 
<emphasis box="[1401,1481,1272,1293]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">quadratus</emphasis>
is characterized by small size (less than half the size of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collinge &amp; Godwin Austen" authorityYear="1895" box="[1369,1482,1298,1320]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pollonerai">
<emphasis box="[1369,1482,1298,1320]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. pollonerai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collinge &amp; Godwin Austen" authorityYear="1895" box="[887,989,1325,1347]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="simrothi">
<emphasis box="[887,989,1325,1347]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. simrothi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), three dark longitudinal stripes on head (shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collinge &amp; Godwin Austen" authorityYear="1895" box="[890,990,1352,1374]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="simrothi">
<emphasis box="[890,990,1352,1374]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. simrothi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but lacking in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collinge &amp; Godwin Austen" authorityYear="1895" box="[1147,1261,1352,1374]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pollonerai">
<emphasis box="[1147,1261,1352,1374]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. pollonerai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1313,1418,1352,1374]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. litteratus</emphasis>
), dark dorsal stripe on tail, kink in dart sac (shared with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collinge &amp; Godwin Austen" authorityYear="1895" box="[1320,1433,1378,1400]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pollonerai">
<emphasis box="[1320,1433,1378,1400]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">M. pollonerai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and reduced receptaculum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="1" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[840,1483,1458,1961]" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis box="[840,937,1459,1480]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Description:</emphasis>
Exterior in adult, preserved specimens (
<figureCitation box="[1363,1471,1458,1481]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="2.[151,215,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[203,1430,152,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[203,1430,152,1662]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 2. External morphology of (presumably) adult Microparmarion exquadratus n. sp. A preserved individual (syntype SP.13561) showing left lateral (A), right lateral (B), ventral (C) and dorsal (D) views. Six of the syntypes (E–J) in living state as photographed in the field in Tawau Hills Park, Sabah." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241760/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Fig. 2A–D</figureCitation>
): Body length 18–21 mm. Shell 8.5–9 mm long, 5 mm wide. Body dull, greyish pink, 3 black dorsal longitudinal stripes, separated by 2 white stripes starting immediately caudal of black eye tentacles and ending ventrally of frontal edge of mantle. Lateral black stripes are half breadth of dorsal stripe. Mantle may also be dull greyish pink, with dark grey mottling. Keeled tail approximately one-third total body length (5–6 mm in adults), with 1 black dorsal stripe. Margin of foot has vertical, dark grey striated pattern. Sole of foot off-white. Tail with caudal horn, not very prominent. Shell semi-transparent, smooth, thin, pale yellow, with faint trace of spiral on right side, approximately 2 whorls. Genital opening visible on right side as short vertical slit. Dark pattern on mantle of 2, nearly continuous lines encircling shell, which are separated by pale greyish-pink ridge with about 10 dark spots.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[840,1483,1458,1961]" lastBlockId="2.[151,794,1779,1961]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">
Live specimens (
<figureCitation box="[1022,1113,1858,1881]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="2.[151,215,1686,1705]" captionTargetBox="[203,1430,152,1662]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[203,1430,152,1662]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 2. External morphology of (presumably) adult Microparmarion exquadratus n. sp. A preserved individual (syntype SP.13561) showing left lateral (A), right lateral (B), ventral (C) and dorsal (D) views. Six of the syntypes (E–J) in living state as photographed in the field in Tawau Hills Park, Sabah." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241760/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="36">Fig. 2E–J</figureCitation>
): Colour dull orange with deep brown pattern. Mantle lobes meet along curved suture, bulging to left, lying left of midline of body. Shell lobes with slight granulation. Frontal part of mantle with slight longitudinal ridges. Caudal horn triangular, slightly longer than wide, pointing caudally. Eye tentacles, when fully extended, as long as shell.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241760/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" startId="2.[151,215,1686,1705]" targetBox="[203,1430,152,1662]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1482,1686,1730]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,241,1686,1705]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Figure 2.</emphasis>
External morphology of (presumably) adult 
<taxonomicName authority="Schilthuizen &amp; Clavera &amp; Khoo &amp; Bondar &amp; Elder &amp; Bouma &amp; Eddington &amp; Reisinger &amp; Cosentino &amp; Rossato &amp; Delledonne, 2019" authorityName="Schilthuizen &amp; Clavera &amp; Khoo &amp; Bondar &amp; Elder &amp; Bouma &amp; Eddington &amp; Reisinger &amp; Cosentino &amp; Rossato &amp; Delledonne" authorityYear="2019" box="[632,844,1687,1707]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="exquadratus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[632,844,1687,1707]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Microparmarion exquadratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[851,900,1687,1706]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A preserved individual (syntype SP.13561) showing left lateral (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1458,1471,1686,1705]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">A</emphasis>
), right lateral (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[262,277,1711,1730]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">B</emphasis>
), ventral (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[363,379,1710,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">C</emphasis>
) and dorsal (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[490,507,1711,1730]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">D</emphasis>
) views. Six of the syntypes (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[744,777,1711,1730]" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">E–J</emphasis>
) in living state as photographed in the field in Tawau Hills Park, Sabah.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,794,1779,1961]" lastBlockId="3.[151,794,1086,1214]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">
Genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[282,344,1832,1854]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="3.[151,215,973,992]" captionTargetBox="[154,789,152,949]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[154,789,152,949]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 3. Genital system of Microparmarion exquadratus n. sp. (syntype SP13560)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241764/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">Figs 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[362,374,1832,1854]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="3.[840,904,915,934]" captionTargetBox="[843,1478,152,891]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[843,1478,152,891]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 4. Dart sac of Microparmarion exquadratus n. sp. (syntype SP13560), cleared with clove oil and showing dart (shaded) in position." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241762/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="37">4</figureCitation>
): Atrium wide. Penis doubly folded into Z-shape, proximally narrow (one-quarter width of atrium), gradually doubling in width, then narrowing to original width distally. Penis sharply folding back on itself as a very narrow tube until half length of proximal part of penis, then folding, broadening, eventually tapering into vas deferens. When following the vas deferens from where it departs from penis, it remains detached from free oviduct until level with middle of dart sac. Vagina short, receptaculum reduced, externally invisible, only discernible after clearing in clove oil. Free oviduct irregularly looped and coiled. Dart sac long, equivalent to combined length of vagina and free oviduct, doubly folded into a Z-shape. Basal portion of dart sac is narrow, containing the dart; middle portion half as long as basal portion, externally somewhat granulate; distal portion inflated, sausage-shaped, 3 times as long as wide, flattened on one side. Dart straight, with gently tapering point, possibly with several low, longitudinal flanges; crown twice as wide as dart.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241762/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" startId="3.[840,904,915,934]" targetBox="[843,1478,152,891]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[840,1483,915,958]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[840,931,915,934]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Dart sac of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schilthuizen &amp; Clavera &amp; Khoo &amp; Bondar &amp; Elder &amp; Bouma &amp; Eddington &amp; Reisinger &amp; Cosentino &amp; Rossato &amp; Delledonne, 2019" authorityName="Schilthuizen &amp; Clavera &amp; Khoo &amp; Bondar &amp; Elder &amp; Bouma &amp; Eddington &amp; Reisinger &amp; Cosentino &amp; Rossato &amp; Delledonne" authorityYear="2019" box="[1044,1256,915,935]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ariophantidae" genus="Microparmarion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="exquadratus" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1044,1256,915,935]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">Microparmarion exquadratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1263,1312,915,934]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(syntype SP13560), cleared with clove oil and showing dart (shaded) in position.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3241764/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="38" startId="3.[151,215,973,992]" targetBox="[154,789,152,949]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,792,973,1017]" pageId="3" pageNumber="38">
